TikTok hides bad videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under 18 years of age.
Imagine China/Reuters
The Chinese social network TikTok censored a video showing Tiananmen Square, Tibet's independence or Falun Gong's illegal religious group, says The Guardian.
The documents before the publication show that the owner of TickTok (ByteDance) is an app that promotes China's foreign policy abroad.
Most of China's policy abuses fall under the “incitement of hatred”.
In each case, TikTok puts bad publications in a context that fits the general rules so that social networking does not look like censorship.
For example, the ban on criticism of China's socialist system falls under a general ban on “criticizing or attacking the policies and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc.”.
The ban on mentioning incidents in the Tiananmen Square or the Cambodian genocide falls under the “discovery of the history of China or other countries”.
The document also contains a list of the prohibited names of the twenty “foreign leaders or statesmen” including the North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sen and Kim Jong Eun, the Indian politicians Mahatmu Gandhi, the American Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, the Japanese premier Sindzo Abe, the South Korean President Park Kyung Hee, the Indonesian President Joko Vidodo and Indian premier Narendra Modi, as listed in the document.
The prohibited material is divided into two categories, as set out in the document.
The first category of publications is removed by social media administrators and may result in the user locking.
Not much of a problem is in the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is restricted to the TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules were obsolete and no longer applied: "We now use a localized approach to modifying, as well as engaging independent local experts."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says the co-founder of the "Producer's Centre" Rustem Bohdanov.
The "Producer's Center" is one Russian media company that officially works with TikTok.
All the advertisements of the "Producer's Center" bloggers work with the social media, but the user's material can be placed without a negotiation, and handed over to the Bohdans.
On the question whether TikTok can talk about politics or Poetin, Boeddenov answers positively and says he's seen similar publications.
The founder of Our Digital Roman Zaripov agreed: "The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: you can't put up shocking content, discriminating remarks, etc.
But under these rules, you can give any content that the monitors don't like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripova is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under 18 years of age.
By user agreement, only persons over 13 years of age can use TikTok.
The social media administrators test their age using artificial intelligence: neurosis analyzes their faces and determines how many years a person looks, tells the Bohdans.
If a neurose determines that the user is younger, its account can be deleted, he adds.
