Since 13 August 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein and Ukraine have joined the list since 1 January 2016.
A decree on the destruction of illegal “sanctions” (the food-embargo products which Moscow had introduced in response to the anti-Russian sanctions of the West) had entered into force in 2015.
In turn, the government has allowed the destruction of “sanctionary” food by any legal means.
As the Western sanctions continued, the Russian Federation also extended its response.
This measure does not apply to products imported by citizens for personal use.
The ban does not concern the import of goods for personal consumption of up to 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Council of the President of the Russian Federation for the Development of Civil Society and Human Rights, Mikhail Fedotov, had previously referred to the “simplely immoral” destruction of food, which he said had a negative effect on the education of people.
Moreover, Rospresnadzor launched an initiative to ban the destruction of food suitable for consumption in early June.
A similar recommendation was then made to the Government by the Human Rights Council of the President of the Russian Federation.
And the vice-premier of the Russian Federation, Alexei Gordeyev, said that it was wrong to destroy food, and we have to think about how we can use it for the purposes of quality.
Head of firm found guilty of tax evasion
By sentence of the Lenin District Court of Ceboxare, the Director of the Land and Law Act of Viacheslav Morozov has been found guilty of the offences set forth in article 1, paragraph 2 (b), of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (exemption from paying taxes on an organization by including in the tax declaration known to be false information of a particularly large size) and article 327 (forgery of an official document granting rights and exoneration for the purpose of its use, committed to conceal and facilitate the commission of another crime).
This is reported by the press service of the SKR Chuwashia Investigative Department.
From January 2008 to December 2009, Vyacheslav Morozov entered information on imperfect transactions into the OLG's tax records.
According to fictitious documents, the company incurred additional costs and hence reduced the amount of value added taxes and the organization's revenue of 11.2 million roubles.
Viacheslav Morozov was sentenced to 3.5 years' suspended imprisonment.
