Chile began building a 1 billion Euro telescope
This is reported by the TASS with a reference to the European Southern observatory (ESO) press service.
This week, the European Extremely Large Telescope has officially begun to build a dome of the E-ELT, so far the most expensive and ambitious ground-based astronomical project.
Its total value is estimated to exceed a billion euros.
Most of this money will be spent on manufacturing equipment and building an observatory.
The most expensive and complex part of the telescope is its record large mirror, whose diameter will be about 39 meters.
It will be collected from 798 hexagonal segments measuring 1.4 meters.
It's a huge mirror, and it's two support surface reflections of a diameter of 4.4 and 3.75 meters, which will help E-ELT get the first detailed images of planets outside the solar system, stars in other galaxies, and find the Earth's doppelgangers.
In addition, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the vicinity of Sgr A*, a supermassive black hole in the center of the Milky Way.
Despite the fact that construction of the dome has just begun, mirrors, scientific tools and other components of the observatory have been developed by scientists, engineers and other professionals for three years since the first E-ELT plans were announced.
A contract for the production of the main mirror, with a total value of about 400 million euros, was received by SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
